            "intermediate_responses": [
              [
                "SearchAgent",
                [
                  {
                    "text": "For a 47-year-old male at average risk for colorectal cancer, current guidelines recommend initiating regular screening. Most individuals in this category should have their first colonoscopy at age 45. If no polyps or abnormalities are found during this initial colonoscopy, the next screening is typically recommended in 10 years. It's important to note that these guidelines are for individuals with an average risk of colorectal cancer. You are considered to be at average risk if you do not have: * A personal history of colorectal cancer or certain types of polyps. * A family history of colorectal cancer. * A personal history of inflammatory bowel disease (such as ulcerative colitis or Crohn's disease). * A confirmed or suspected hereditary colorectal cancer syndrome (like familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) or Lynch syndrome). * A personal history of radiation to the abdomen or pelvic area to treat a prior cancer. If any of these risk factors apply, you may need to begin screening earlier, be screened more frequently, or undergo specific types of tests. For example, if you have a first-degree relative (parent or sibling) with a history of colorectal cancer, screening might be recommended at age 40, or 10 years younger than the age at which your family member was diagnosed, whichever is earlier. While colonoscopy is considered the \"gold standard\" for colorectal cancer screening, other screening options are available. These include stool-based tests (like FIT or gFOBT annually, or a multi-targeted stool DNA test every three years) and other visual exams (such as CT colonography or flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years). If a non-colonoscopy screening test yields an abnormal result, a follow-up colonoscopy is typically required. For individuals aged 45-75, regular screening is recommended. The decision to continue screening after age 75 should be made in consultation with a doctor, considering individual health and prior screening history."
                  }
                ]
              ],
